mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">heavily regulated</a>, though y=
ou hear about it less. That regulation is just less controversial. There ar=
e material and debatable trade-offs in bank capital and liquidity regulatio=
n: A bank with tons of capital will be safer, but it will also have less ca=
pacity to lend to the real economy, so there are debates=C2=A0about what th=
e optimal level of capital should be. Whereas with keeping track of the mon=
ey, there are fewer trade-offs. Banks should=C2=A0<em>entirely=C2=A0</em>ke=
ep track of the money.=C2=A0Nobody is lobbying for =E2=80=9Cactually bank l=
edgers should be a bit more loosey-goosey.=E2=80=9D The proper amount of lo=
sing track of the money is none.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And this r=
isk is=C2=A0harder to fix after the fact. If a bank loses all your money, t=
he FDIC can give you your money back, because the FDIC is the government an=
d can print money. If the bank loses its=C2=A0<em>list=C2=A0</em>of who has=
 the money, what can the FDIC do=3F You can go to the FDIC and say =E2=80=
=9Cthat bank owes me $100,=E2=80=9D but=C2=A0<em>anyone=C2=A0</em>can say t=
hat, whether or not it is true. The definitive list of who the bank owes mo=
ney is kept by the bank. Unless it isn=E2=80=99t. If the bank doesn=E2=80=
=99t keep a definitive list, then nobody does.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
